elebrates its silver anniversary with this bracing collection of original essays by world-renowned scholars, directors, actors, and critics.Chicago Shakespeare Theater unveils the artistic visions and decisions that helped shape this venerable institution and examines the theater's international reputation for staging such remarkable and provocative performances. The volume brings together works by such heralded drama critics as Terry Teachout, Jonathan Abarbanel, and Michael Billington; theater industry giants like Michael Bogdanov, Edward Hall, and Simon Callow; interviews with the Chicago Shakespeare Theater's own Artistic Director Barbara Gaines and Executive Director Criss Henderson; and essays by such noted figures in academe as Clark Hulse, Wendy Wall, and Michael Shapiro.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aTheaterzIllinoiszChicagoxHistory. 0aTheatrical companieszIllinoiszChicagoxHistory. 4aArt History. 4aMidwest. 4aPerforming Arts & Drama. 7aDRAMA / Shakespeare.2bisacsh  aMichael Shapiro, Wendy Wall, Clark Hulse, Chicago Shakes, theatrical tradition of Chicago.1 aAbarbanel, Jonathan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBillington, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBuccola, Regina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCallow, Simon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDi Salvo, Gina M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDoniger, Wendy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGore, Jeffrey, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGreenburg, Bradley, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHulse, Clark, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/voc